              There is considerable consensus between the major parties on
              pursuing broadly open trade and investment policies,
              notwithstanding some specific areas of disagreement. In a
              difficult international context, the Coalition government did
              well to work with other countries, notably Japan, to get the
              CPTPP over the line after the US withdrew. Labor has supported
              the CPTPP but taken issue with certain elements, notably the
              waiving of labour market testing for temporary foreign workers
              and the inclusion of investor state dispute settlement (ISDS)
              provisions.
              
              Though politically salient, the economic consequences of
              requiring labour market testing may not be especially material.
              Firms generally prefer to use local labour where they can, other
              visa requirements to avoid undercutting the local labour market
              still apply, and existing labour market testing rules are in any
              case not overly stringent.
              
              With regard to ISDS, many economists, including Australia’s
              Productivity Commission, question whether this actually
              facilitates much cross-border investment, especially enough to
              justify the risk of foreign companies challenging government
              policies or otherwise causing ‘regulatory chill’ detrimental to
              the public interest in areas like health and the environment.
              Having said this, the CPTPP actually replaced existing ISDS
              provisions in other agreements while adding more protections
              aimed at preventing such problems.
              
              Labor has also said it would change the way future free-trade
              agreements are negotiated to bring more transparency around the
              process and independent assessment of the potential economic and
              social impacts. These are useful steps to strengthen community
              confidence in such agreements.

